Initial rationale: I’ll start from the hypothesis that end-to-end deep learning on raw binaries should outperform traditional malware pipelines because it avoids brittle hand-engineered features. The planned method is a MalConv-style byte-level neural network, possibly upgraded with transformers or long-context convolutions to ingest full PE files directly.

```action search
{
  "query": "raw binary malware detection deep learning MalConv robustness obfuscation adversarial packing benchmark recent"
}
```

[result] Recent and established work already covers this direction: MalConv and later raw-byte neural malware detectors learn directly from executable bytes, but multiple studies show they are brittle under packing, padding, section injection, adversarial byte perturbations, and distribution shift. Benchmarks such as EMBER-style PE classification and adversarial malware studies report that raw-byte models can achieve high in-distribution accuracy while failing under realistic obfuscation or adversarial transformations. This suggests that “raw binaries end-to-end will outperform traditional methods” is not robustly supported.

Actually, this changes things: the initial method choice is already well explored, and the evidence contradicts the assumption that raw end-to-end learning is sufficient. Raw-byte DNNs are strong baselines, but the recent literature shows they are vulnerable to exactly the transformations malware authors use. I should pivot away from “just train a larger raw-byte model” and instead propose a hybrid static-dynamic detector that combines neural learning with interpretable, manipulation-resistant behavioral and structural features.

```action search
{
  "query": "hybrid static dynamic malware detection interpretable features deep learning robustness obfuscation adversarial malware"
}
```

[result] Hybrid approaches combining static PE metadata/import graphs/control-flow indicators with dynamic sandbox traces/API-call sequences/network/file-system behavior are commonly reported as more robust to packing and obfuscation than purely static raw-byte models. Interpretable features such as imported APIs, permission/section anomalies, syscall/API-call motifs, registry/file/network behaviors, and attribution over behavioral events help analysts validate detections and reduce blind reliance on opaque byte patterns.

