Initial rationale: I’ll first test the case for prioritizing green hydrogen in residential heating. The hypothesis would be that if hydrogen can reuse gas networks cheaply and gain consumer acceptance, it might merit priority despite lower end-use efficiency than electrification. I’ll look for recent evidence on efficiency, infrastructure cost, and adoption/trials. 

```action
{"tool":"search","query":"green hydrogen residential heating efficiency heat pumps infrastructure cost consumer acceptance trials evidence"}
``` 

```result
{
  "findings": [
    {
      "source": "IEA and multiple energy-system reviews",
      "evidence": "Using renewable electricity to make green hydrogen and burn it in boilers delivers far less heat per kWh of electricity than using that electricity in heat pumps; heat pumps commonly deliver 2.5–4+ units of heat per unit of electricity, while electrolysis plus boiler combustion loses substantial energy."
    },
    {
      "source": "UK hydrogen village trial reporting and policy coverage",
      "evidence": "Several proposed hydrogen-for-heating community trials faced local opposition and/or were cancelled or scaled back, indicating consumer acceptance and delivery uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "source": "Hydrogen network conversion studies",
      "evidence": "Hydrogen would require appliance replacement, safety management, metering/regulator upgrades, storage buildout, and in many cases pipeline assessment or replacement; blending into gas grids offers only limited emissions reductions."
    }
  ]
}
``` 

Actually, this contradicts the initial “reuse gas networks cheaply and win adoption” assumption. The evidence says the key dependency for prioritizing residential hydrogen—cheap infrastructure conversion plus consumer acceptance—is not yet realized, and efficiency is structurally unfavorable versus heat pumps. This changes the direction: instead of prioritizing green hydrogen for homes, the policy should reserve scarce green hydrogen for harder-to-electrify uses and prioritize heat pumps, building efficiency, and district heating where appropriate. I’ll do one more check on the best alternative allocation of green hydrogen. 

```action
{"tool":"search","query":"best uses of green hydrogen hard to electrify industry steel ammonia shipping residential heating comparison"}
``` 

